    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-02-16T08:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-02-16T08:30:00-05:00" n="69"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d69">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.20 Missions/2–1648: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Allen</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-02-16T17:00:00+03:30"
                            >February 16, 1948—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>189. During my farewell call<note n="1" xml:id="d69fn1">Ambassador Allen was
                        returning to Washington to serve as Assistant Secretary of State for Public
                        Affairs.</note> on Prime Minister today I expressed concurrence in
                    Ambassador Ala’s recommendation (Dept’s 131, <pb facs="0124" n="110"
                        xml:id="pg_110"/> February 10) that Iran Government submit to UN Soviet note
                    of January 31 and Iranian reply. Prime Minister said he agreed but asked whether
                    I thought Soviets would be seriously annoyed by such action. I said they would
                    undoubtedly be displeased but that any disadvantage on this score would be more
                    than offset by advantage of letting Soviets and world know that Iran had
                    confidence in UN and that Soviets could not expect to write notes of this kind
                    without having them brought to attention of world organization. I said that for
                    action to be effective it must have no appearance of having been prompted.</p>
                <p>Hakimi gave every indication of intention to send notes to Secretary General for
                        <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> information.</p>
                <p>Sent Department as 189, repeated London as 20.</p>
                <p>Department pass Moscow as 12.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Allen</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
